 spells use mana, energy, etc. that recharges over time or is it a so many spells per day thing.<br><br>5. How is soloing in comparison to EQ? Is it easier, the same, or harder? <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/bprexus95980.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=mofftarkin>Moff Tarkin</A> at: 3/16/02 10:40:23 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uchabisu.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Chabisu</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/17/02 3:28:50 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: General Questions</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 1. How crowded is the game world. If some areas are popular that is ok but if everything is camped like in EQ then that might be a problem for me.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>When I quit playing there were some hotspot leveling areas while there were still tons of places left to go.  The hotspots tended to be the dungeons because at the time that was where most of the better gear dropped.  Last I heard though they were planning to add better drops to outdoor monsters also so it shouldn't be like you're forced to hunt in a dungeon.<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 2. I hear you need to get weapons repaired and at somtime replaced. Do you get enough money on average to keep up repairs on your stuff?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>It isn't as bad as most people think.  Weapons and armor (jewelry items also) do need repairing at times.  But, in most places you are hunting you should be making enough in loot/coin that it shouldn't be a big deal.  After you level a bit higher you start making more and more coin and at the highest levels it really isn't a big deal about finding money.  Though it does suck that after so many repairs you pretty much do have to buy a new item (except for jewelry items).<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 3. If you die do you lose xp and if so how much. Can you lose a level of just go to minumum xp for your current.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>You do loose exp (if you go back for your body you will get most, but not all back) when you die.  But unlike EQ you only can go to the minium amount of exp for your current level.  When you die though you will loose Constitution points which you must buy back.<br><br><br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 4. Do spells use mana, energy, etc. that recharges over time or is it a so many spells per day thing.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Spells are on a mana/energy system like in EQ.  The huge difference though is the regen rate on it.  From 0% mana to 100% mana only takes a few minutes instead of nearly ten like in EQ.  Unless you're soloing you'll never run out of mana in exp groups.<br><br><!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><b><i>Quote:</i></b><hr> 5. How is soloing in comparison to EQ? Is it easier, the same, or harder?<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br><br>Soloing can be done by every class in the game to some extent at least.  For some it is a cakewalk, for some it is harder and might take a little more downtime.  But every class has the option to solo for exp.  If you only have thirty minutes you can log on and kill a few monsters with no problems almost always.<br><br>---<br><br>Overall I still think DAoC is a better game than EQ.  But friends are hard to shake so I'm back here instead of over there. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/uarkanissoulhart.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Arkanis Soulhart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/17/02 10:44:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=2>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://members.home.net/1jmorales1/MO60x60.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: General Questions</span><hr size=1> One thing to keep in mind, if you are coming to DAoC thinking its going to be a carbon copy of EQ, your going to be disappointed.  DAoC is a PvP game first, PvE game second (it's the opposite in EQ).  You purpose for leveling and gaining skills is primary for RvR.  Loot takes a backseat in this game.  Also understand that DAoC does not have the content that a EQ +3 expansions has.  But, the game mechanics are better, the graphics are better, and the community is (dare I say) friendlier.  If your looking for those kind of things in a game, you'll like it alot. <p><HTML><BODY><p align="center"><img src="http://home.mchsi.com/~1jmorales1/Soloris1.jpg" width="300"  height="55" /><BR><h5 align="center"><color=#FFoo33">Level 12 Eldritch</p><BR><img src="http://home.mchsi.com/~1jmorales1/Arkanis1.jpg" width="300"  height="55" /></p><align="center"><color=#FFoo33">Level 20 Champion<BR><a href="http://www.jesserenhard.com/mysticorder2/">The Mystic Order</a></h5></BODY></HTML></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#F5F5DC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ushandael.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Shandael</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://members.aol.com/angshan/sapphyre.jpg" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/20/02 12:36:13 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=3>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: General Questions</span><hr size=1> ----------------------------------------------------------<br>1. How crowded is the game world. If some areas are popular that is ok but if everything is camped like in EQ then that might be a problem for me.<br>----------------------------------------------------------<br><br>The gameworld isn't as crowded as in EQ, mainly because the zones are so much larger in DAoC. The dungeons can pick up crowds, but since loot drops are more spread out among mobs there's no camping for a particular spawn that leads to the timesink or camp lists like EQ. So if one intersection/hallway/room of a dungeon is camped, just find another. For the most part you'll still have the same chance at loot drops as as anywhere else in the vicinity.<br><br>----------------------------------------------------------<br>2. I hear you need to get weapons repaired and at somtime replaced. Do you get enough money on average to keep up repairs on your stuff?<br>----------------------------------------------------------<br><br>It's usually easy to keep up with repairs, and if you take one of the main trade skills, such as armorcrafting or weaponcrafting, you can repair your own stuff without cost. Either way, the money/vendor fodder items are very well balanced to your level, so it's not really a strain to pay for repairs, and in most cases you'll outgrow your armor before it becomes unrepairable.<br><br>Armor costs are also well balanced and in line with player levels. You won't find plate mail for 4000 plat like you do in EQ. It's more like 8 gold, depending on the type.<br><br>----------------------------------------------------------- <br>3. If you die do you lose xp and if so how much. Can you lose a level of just go to minumum xp for your current.<br>-----------------------------------------------------------<br><br>First, you can never lose a level, no matter how many times you're killed. <br><br>Second, when you die, you appear back at your bind point with all of your gear, so no biggie. You leave a tombstone where you died at, and you lose 1 - 3 points of Constitution depending on how many times you died at that level, which can easily be bought back from any NPC healer. <br><br>If you go back to your tombstone and pray at it you'll gain all your xp back except 5 percent. So basically you lose 5 percent of your xp when you die. Same if you're rezzed, except there's no tombstone, no need to buy back Constitution points, and you still only get the 5 percent xp penalty.<br><br>Also, most healer types get rezz at 10th lvl, and even hybrids, such as paladins, get it at 30th, so it's much easier getting a rezz than in EQ.<br><br>----------------------------------------------------------<br>4. Do spells use mana, energy, etc. that recharges over time or is it a so many spells per day thing.<br>----------------------------------------------------------<br><br>It's just like EQ. You have a mana bar, and every time you case a spell you drain some of the bar. <br><br>The difference in DAoC is that the mana regen rate is SO much faster that you can practically chain-cast spells til a mob is dead, sit for a very short time; seconds to maybe 3 minutes at the highest levels, to fully restore your mana.<br><br>It's beautiful...&lt;sniff, sniff&gt;...just beautiful...<br><br>----------------------------------------------------------<br>5. How is soloing in comparison to EQ? Is it easier, the same, or harder? <br>----------------------------------------------------------<br><br>Soloing is MUCH easier in DAoC. Every class can solo, and with the speedy hp/mana regen, you can be near death one minute and fully restored and ready to go again the next.<br><br>Every class can solo. Some can do it faster and easier than others, but without exception, every class can solo. Take for instance clerics. You can specialize your cleric to what is called a &quot;Smite Cleric&quot; who has stuns and damage spells. That character can solo much faster and easier than the same cleric that specialized towards healing and buffs, but both can solo. It's just the Smite cleric might be able to solo Yellows where the Heal-based cleric should probably stick to blues. But since the Heal-based cleric is specialized towards heals, including insta-heals and buffs, even they can probably tackle yellows. It will take them longer to kill it, but it can be done.<br><br>- Sapphyre<br>   Pellinor/Albion<br>   29th Paladin<br> <p><img src=http://members.aol.com/angshan/Sapp1.jpg><BR> Remembrances of past glories<BR>Is the fire of future endeavors.</p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/udica.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Dica</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/poll_icon.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(3/22/02 12:29:18 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980frm17.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=211.topic&index=4>Reply</a>    <br>Community Supporter<br> </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: General Questions</span><hr size=1> 1. See 2<br>2. See 3<br>3. See 4<br>4. See 5<